As the consequences of inactivity are severe and have a worldwide effect, ensuring action to combat climate change is unquestionably a crucial priority in climate policy formulation. When developing climate policy, it is vital to also address ethical considerations. The equitable distribution of the cost of climate change mitigation across nations and people is a significant ethical problem. Historically, developed nations have been the greatest emitters of greenhouse gases, while poorer nations will frequently be disproportionately impacted by the effects of climate change. Consequently, it is essential that climate policy take into consideration the concept of shared but differentiated duties, which recognizes that industrialized nations have a higher obligation to mitigate climate change since they have contributed more to the issue. The possible effect of climate policies on disadvantaged populations is another ethical problem. Climate policy may have a considerable influence on the lives and livelihoods of individuals, especially those who are already living in poverty or are marginalized in other ways. Therefore, it is essential that climate policy be formulated so as to safeguard and assist these vulnerable groups. In addition, it is essential to evaluate the ethical implications of the technologies and strategies employed to ameliorate climate change. The large-scale implementation of bioenergy with carbon capture and storage (BECCS), for instance, presents ethical considerations about land usage and food security. In conclusion, guaranteeing action to reduce climate change is essential, but it should not be the only factor considered when formulating climate policy. Ethical problems, including equality, the protection of vulnerable people, and the ethical implications of the technology employed to combat climate change must also be considered. Ignoring these ethical considerations might result in unforeseen repercussions and eventually compromise the efficacy of climate policy. 